I cannot doubt that, had Cicero chosen, the Triumvirate might have been a Quattuorvirat03 † but he is faithful to his causa optima, the defection of Pompeius from which he regrets in expressive phrase (Att. ii 21, 3, 4). His only comfort is that he has now no rival in Pompeius for the plaudits of posterity (Att. ii. 17, 2). Clodius having gained his tribunate by concealing his designs against Cicero (a strong proof that Cicero was not the object of popular resentment)‚ at once proceeds to his revenge. Aster several enactments‚ having a tendency to conciliate the various classes of Roman society, he proposes a law enacting that anyone who had put Roman citizens to death without trial should be interdicted from fire and water.
